Best Practices

AI praise-giving tool promises ‘authentic’ insights
Irish company Workhuman says new technology can help workers feel more valued. (Workhuman users are including staff at BP, Cisco and LinkedIn). The new AI element makes these more accurate by indicating appropriate reward levels, within budgets set by companies.
The benefit for managers is the crowdsourced data AI can deliver — from pinpointing mentors with the right skills to spotting the high-performing staff companies should retain.

Perspectives

The Power of Being an Amateur
In today’s business culture, expertise is currency. We celebrate mastery, reward pattern recognition, and prize leaders who can quickly distinguish signal from noise. But in doing so, we’ve created an unexpected trap for ourselves: The more we become “somebody” in your chosen field (recognized, accomplished, authoritative), the more our thinking tends to calcify, limiting your flexibility and creativity.
📘 style="color:#eb1000;">Inspired by: The management scholar Erik Dane has called this problem “cognitive entrenchment,” and the researchers Huy Phan and Bing Hiong Ngu have documented it widely across professions.

⚙️ Did You Know?

What is a “Digital Twin of the Employee”?
The idea of “digital twins” isn’t just for factories or machines anymore—it’s entering the workplace. A digital twin of the employee is a virtual profile that simulates an individual’s skills, career trajectory, and development needs using AI and people data.
🔍 Companies like Siemens and Accenture are experimenting with these models to personalize learning, predict career paths, and identify future skill gaps.
🚀 style="color:#eb1000;">Why it's cool: Imagine EX being able to forecast which skills your team will need in 18 months and proactively design learning journeys—before the gap even appears.
